s have further accelerated this change. They discuss older visual technologies, such as videotape evidence, and then current and future uses of visual and multimedia digital technologies, including trial presentation software and interactive multimedia. They also describe how law itself is going online, in the form of virtual courts, cyberjuries, and more, and explore the implications of law’s movement to computer screens. Throughout Law on Display, the authors illustrate their analysis with examples from a wide range of actual trials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic discovery (Law)zUnited States. 0aElectronic evidencexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aElectronic recordsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEvidence, DocumentaryzUnited States. 0aVideo tapes in court proceedingszUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aChristina.  aFeigenson.  aNeal.  aSpiesel.  aaccelerated.  aanalysis.  aboth.  achange.  acomprehensive.  aculture.  adependent.  adeveloping.  adriven.  aenvironment.  aexplain.  afrom.  afurther.  ahave.  ahow.  aimages.  alargely.  alaw.  alegal.  amore.  amoved.  apractice.  arapidly.  asurvey.  atechnologies.  athis.  atransforming.  avisual.  awhen.  awords-only.1 aSpiesel, Christina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814727584.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728567/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL 